Here is the refined, unified guide. I’ve updated the library names and the hardware logic based on our discovery that you're using the BME280 version of the Waveshare HAT.
🛠 Waveshare Environment HAT: Quick Start Guide

Target System: Raspberry Pi OS (Bookworm/Bullseye)
Hardware: Pi 5 / 4B / Zero 2W
1. Enable Hardware Interfaces

The I2C bus is turned off by default for security. You must enable it to communicate with the sensors.
Bash

sudo raspi-config
# Navigate to: Interface Options -> I2C -> Yes
# Select 'Finish' and reboot if prompted.

2. Install System Dependencies

The Pi 5 uses a specific architecture (RP1 chip) for GPIO. We need python3-lgpio to ensure the Python libraries can talk to the pins.
Bash

sudo apt update
sudo apt install python3-pip python3-venv i2c-tools python3-lgpio -y

3. Setup Virtual Environment

Raspberry Pi OS now enforces "Externally Managed Environments." You must use a virtual environment to install Python packages.
Bash

python -m venv env
source env/bin/activate

4. Install Python Drivers

These are the specific drivers for the Waveshare sensor suite.

    Note: We use adafruit-circuitpython-bme280 because your HAT uses the 0x76 address for Temp/Hum/Pressure.

Bash

# Core tools
pip install customtkinter matplotlib board adafruit-blinka rpi-lgpio

# Sensor specific drivers
pip install adafruit-circuitpython-bme280 \
adafruit-circuitpython-sgp40 \
adafruit-circuitpython-tsl2591 \
adafruit-circuitpython-ltr390

5. Hardware Verification

Run this command to ensure the HAT is seated correctly and the Pi sees the chips:
Bash

i2cdetect -y 1

Expected Output:

    29: TSL2591 (Light)

    53: LTR390 (UV)

    68: ICM20948 (Motion/RTC)

    76: BME280 (Temp/Hum/Baro)

    59: SGP40 (VOC - Note: may only appear after script starts)

🐧 Running on Ubuntu? (Addendum)

If you are using Ubuntu instead of Pi OS, follow the steps above with these two critical changes:

    Permissions: Ubuntu doesn't grant I2C access by default. Run:
    Bash

sudo usermod -aG i2c,gpio $USER

(Logout and login for this to take effect)

Dependencies: Use libgpiod if lgpio behaves unexpectedly:
Bash

    sudo apt install libgpiod-dev python3-libgpiod -y

🚀 Final Check

Once your environment is ready, you can launch your script:
Bash

python dashboard.py
